<h2 class="learn-heading">Learn: The New Leash Rules</h2>

<div class="info-box">
  <h3>üêï HEAR YE!<br>These are the new rules of the leash henceforth!!!</h3>
  <p>From this point forward, the leash has two modes. Either it's relaxed (good!) or it's tight (bad!). When the leash is relaxed, we keep moving. When the leash gets tight, we stop immediately and wait. The dog needs to understand that pulling = no progress.</p>
</div>

<div class="exercise-section">
  <h3>Exercise: Outside U-Turns</h3>

  <p>Start outside in a low-distraction area with your dog on leash.</p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Start walking</strong> with your dog on leash in a low-distraction area.</li>
    <li><strong>The instant</strong> you feel tension on the leash, stop moving.</li>
    <li><strong>Stand still</strong> like a tree. Don't pull back, don't say anything.</li>
    <li><strong>Wait</strong> for your dog to look at you or move back toward you.</li>
    <li><strong>Mark and reward</strong>, then resume walking.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>Your dog will learn: tight leash = no progress. Loose leash = we keep moving toward interesting things.</p>
</div>

<div class="tips-box">
  <h3>Tips and Tricks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>‚òùÔ∏è This takes patience. You might stop 50 times in the first five minutes. That's normal!</li>
    <li>‚òùÔ∏è Don't pull them back to you. Wait for them to choose to relieve the pressure.</li>
    <li>‚òùÔ∏è Pick a boring, familiar area for practice. Save the exciting park for later.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="exercise-section">
  <h3>Exercise: Inside U-Turns</h3>

  <p>For dogs who are really determined pullers, stopping isn't enough. We need to make pulling actively unrewarding. Try practicing inside where the environment is less stimulating.</p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Start walking</strong> with your dog inside your home.</li>
    <li><strong>When the leash goes tight</strong>, immediately turn 180¬∞ and walk the other direction.</li>
    <li><strong>Don't announce it</strong> - just turn. Use gentle leash pressure to guide them.</li>
    <li><strong>Mark and reward</strong> when they catch up to your side.</li>
    <li><strong>Repeat</strong> as many times as necessary.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>This teaches: "If you pull, we go away from the thing you wanted to investigate."</p>
</div>

<div class="tips-box">
  <h3>Tips and Tricks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>‚òùÔ∏è Change directions frequently to keep your dog paying attention to you.</li>
    <li>‚òùÔ∏è Reward heavily when they're walking nicely at your side.</li>
    <li>‚òùÔ∏è Practice in your driveway or yard first before going to exciting locations.</li>
